  "1": {
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "Such statements, rather than occurring\nrandomly in the text, signal the introduction of\na new topic or a different audience.\n(2) The Deity\u2019s various instructions, introduced in the previously\nmentioned fashion, are set within brief narrative frameworks. For\nexample, the narrative sequence with which Exodus ended (40:38)\n[v_Lev_8_1] and that is resumed at Leviticus 8:1, has been interrupted by edito-\nrially inserted instructions (Lev 1\u20137). Thus Exodus ends with the\nreport that the construction of a portable sanctuary (\u201cthe tent of\nmeeting\u201d) in the period of \u201cwandering in the wilderness\u201d has now\nbeen completed. The next and necessary step in order for it to\nbecome operational would be the appointment and consecration of\n[v_Lev_8_1] a priesthood. It is only at Leviticus 8:1 that this necessary step\nmaterializes, when the Deity instructs Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` as follows: \u201cTake\nAaron `[char_Aaron_Exo_6]` and his sons . . . and assemble the whole congregation . . .\u201d\n[v_Lev_1_1] The intervening material (Lev 1:1\u20137:38), however, presupposes\nthat the priesthood is, in fact, already \u201cup and running.\u201d This illog-\nical kind of literary sequence is more likely to result from editorial\nactivity than from authorship. [Editorial Process]",
    "Andrew Bonar, Andrew E. Hill": ", 2).\nVer. 1,"
  },
